{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505904"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:37:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:37:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2496"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2496"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.05,0.12,0.02,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2496"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96828"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2496"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2496"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79443"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1075"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12730"},{"type":"tags","id":"12756"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45494"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96828"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old Indigenous boy is brought to the Emergency Department by his mother with a papular erythematous eruption across most of his body. She reports he has been scratching for the last week. He is not sleeping due to the itch and is struggling to concentrate at school however otherwise been feeling systemically well. He has a history of eczema but his mother reports it has never been this extensive before. They live in a house with 12 occupants in total over three generations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his vital parameters are within normal limits. There are multiple excoriated erythematous papules, predominantly in acral sites. On examination of the web spaces with dermoscopy you notice the characteristic \u0027delta sign\u0027 and the \u2018jet with contrail pattern\u2019. There are several areas of the patients skin that appear to be secondarily infected.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a possible consequence of this skin condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glomerulonephritis","Ischaemic heart disease","Liver disease","Early onset dementia","Non-melanoma skin cancer"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical history and examination findings are consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Escabies infestation\u003C/strong\u003E. Severe itch often causes sleep disturbance and reduced productivity. This is particularly important for children as this can subsequently lead on to poor childhood development. Symptoms usually resolve within a few days of completing treatment, however the rash and pruritis may take four to six weeks to resolve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EScabies is often complicated by local skin and soft tissue infections with \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E due to scratching-induced trauma. Localised infections that are untreated can lead to cellulitis, abscesses, and sepsis. Systemic infections with \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E can cause acute post-streptococcal \u003Cstrong\u003Eglomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E and acute rheumatic fever. These conditions can develop into chronic kidney disease and chronic rheumatic heart disease respectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInfestations of the scabies mite do not directly result in \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver disease\u003C/strong\u003E. Severe sepsis occurring in the context of scabies may cause acute liver injury alongside multiorgan failure, however this would be an unlikely scenario. Poor concentration and sleep disturbance may appear consistent with reduced cognition, however scabies is not associated with development of \u003Cstrong\u003Eearly onset dementia\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003ENon-melanoma skin cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is not associated with scabies. Chronic rheumatic heart disease is a risk factor for other cardiac diseases including \u003Cstrong\u003Eischaemic heart disease\u003C/strong\u003E, however ischaemic heart disease is not the best option in the above list.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Scabies infestation has several local and systemic consequences, including: impetigo, Streptococcal or Staphylococcal sepsis, renal disease, cardiac disease and social implications."],"references":["Engelman D, Yoshizumi J, Hay RJ, Osti M, Micali G, et al. The 2020 International Alliance for the Control of Scabies Consensus Criteria for the Diagnosis of Scabies. Br J Dermatol. 2020;183(5):808-820. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7687112/","Thomas C, Coates SJ, Engelman D, Chosidow O, Chang AY. Ectoparasites: Scabies. J Am Acad Dermatol. 2020;82(3):533-548. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31310840/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79443"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2496"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79443"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T22:50:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-11T21:16:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2496"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96828"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1063"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Rash","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-06-11T11:19:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-28T16:03:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"3"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCou